git-inject - Apply patch diffs to a target commit

`git inject` collects the changes in a patch
commit on the specified branch, then applies
the patch diffs to the target commit.




USAGE

git inject <target> [<patch>]
           [<target>] (--working-tree | --staged)
           [<target>] --file [FILE...]
git inject (--continue | --abort | --revert)
git inject --clear




INSTALLATION

Copy and paste this command in a terminal.
Elevated privileges are necessary to install the
git-inject documentation.


      curl -fsSL https://dl.clitson.nl/git-inject | sh


To run the installer locally, clone the
repository and then run the installation script
in an elevated terminal.


      chmod +x install.sh
      ./install.sh --local


Run 'git help inject' after installation to view
the full documentation or view the HTML document
in this repository at https://cdn.clitson.nl/git-inject/docs




EXAMPLES

Merge the current `HEAD` into an older commit:


      git inject fe8fd5d
      git inject --into fe8fd5d
      git inject HEAD~3


Merge a specific commit into an older commit:


      git inject fe8fd5d c644e39
      git inject HEAD~7 HEAD^


Inject a patch into a different branch:


      git inject --branch develop fe8fd5d c644e39
      git inject fe8fd5d c644e39 -b develop


Inject changes and automatically resolve conflicts
in favor of the patch:


      git inject fe8fd5d c644e39 --theirs


Inject all changes in the working tree:


      git inject --working-tree
      git inject -w fe8fd5d


Inject staged changes into an older commit:


      git inject -s
      git inject --staged fe8fd5d


Inject specific files into an older commit:


      git inject HEAD~2 --file src/main.c


Resolve a conflict during injection:


      # Edit conflicting files then
      git add [FILE...]
      git inject --continue




SANDOX & TESTING

To create a temporary sandbox to test the command,
clone the repository then run


      chmod +x ./test/sandbox
      ./test/sandbox setup


and navigate to the 'git-inject-sandbox/' folder
and open the git project.

The sandbox is crated with six branches, two of
which are orphan branches and the other four are
split between the orphans, two each. The included
files are designed to be distinguishable from each
other by file extension.

A predefined suite of tests can be run with


      chmod +x ./test/evaluation
      ./test/evaluation


to test the functionality of git-inject.




